06593nam a22007695i 9780292793675DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212009txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927936757 a10.7560/7067122doi  a(DE-B1597)588292  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGN347 ǂb V54 2009eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a30100aViewpoints :bVisual Anthropologists at Work /ced. by Mary Strong, Laena Wilder. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (431 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tHistorical Foreword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSection I PHOTOGRAPHY NOW -- tCHAPTER 1 Photographic Exploration of Social and Cultural Experience -- tCHAPTER 2 Documentary Photography in the Field -- tCHAPTER 3 Photography and Ethnography -- tSection II IMAGES FROM THE PAST -- tCHAPTER 4 Historical Photographs of North American Indians: Primary Documents, BUT View with Care -- tCHAPTER 5 Blasting a Boulder and Building Memories -- tSection III MOVING PICTURES: FILM, VIDEO, AND COMPUTERGENERATED MEDIA -- tCHAPTER 6 Reading the Mind of the Ethnographic Filmmaker: Mining a Flawed Genre for Anthropological Content -- tCHAPTER 7 Visual Anthropology in a Time of War: Intimacy and Interactivity in Ethnographic Media -- tCHAPTER 8 Guestworkers: Farmworkers, Filmmakers, and Their Obligations in the Field -- tSection IV ROADS LESS TRAVELED: UNUSUAL SUBFIELDS -- tPart I UNCOMMON SUBJECT AREAS -- tCHAPTER 9 Envisioning Primates -- tCHAPTER 10 Steps to an Ethnography of Dance -- tCHAPTER 11 Looking for the Past in the Present Ethnoarchaeology at al-Hiba -- tPart II Media BEYOND CAMERA WORK -- tCHAPTER 12 In Search of Live Relics in Cold Lake -- tCHAPTER 13 Art and Mind Working on Murals -- tCHAPTER 14 Art History and Anthropology: LOULY PEACOCK KONZ and JAMES PEACOCK -- tSECTION V Epilogue -- tCHAPTER 15 Elementary Forms of the Digital Media Tools for Applied Action Collaboration and Research in Visual Anthropology -- tGlossary -- tAuthor Biographies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly in its history, anthropology was a visual as well as verbal discipline. But as time passed, visually oriented professionals became a minority among their colleagues, and most anthropologists used written words rather than audiovisual modes as their professional means of communication. Today, however, contemporary electronic and interactive media once more place visual anthropologists and anthropologically oriented artists within the mainstream. Digital media, small-sized and easy-to-use equipment, and the Internet, with its interactive and public forum websites, democratize roles once relegated to highly trained professionals alone. However, having access to a good set of tools does not guarantee accurate and reliable work. Visual anthropology involves much more than media alone. This book presents visual anthropology as a work-in-progress, open to the myriad innovations that the new audiovisual communications technologies bring to the field. It is intended to aid in contextualizing, explaining, and humanizing the storehouse of visual knowledge that university students and general readers now encounter, and to help inform them about how these new media tools can be used for intellectually and socially beneficial purposes. Concentrating on documentary photography and ethnographic film, as well as lesser-known areas of study and presentation including dance, painting, architecture, archaeology, and primate research, the book's fifteen contributors feature populations living on all of the world's continents as well as within the United States. The final chapter gives readers practical advice about how to use the most current digital and interactive technologies to present research findings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aVisual anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAdra, Najwa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiella, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollier, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlowerday, Julie M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHermer, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMclain, Kimowan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOchsenschlager, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScherer, Joanna Cohan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrong, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrong, Mary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThompson, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilder, Laena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilder, Laena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZeller, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292793675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292793675/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK